What is a Helm Chart?

Definition

A Helm Chart is a package that contains all the files needed to deploy an application on Kubernetes.
---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

We'll create our first chart:

    helm create springboot-app

    You'll see:

    springboot-app/
    │
    ├── Chart.yaml
    ├── values.yaml
    ├── charts/
    ├── templates/
    │   ├── deployment.yaml
    │   ├── service.yaml
    │   ├── ingress.yaml
    │   ├── serviceaccount.yaml
    │   ├── hpa.yaml
    │   ├── _helpers.tpl
    │   └── NOTES.txt
    └── .helmignore

what is inside the 

chart.yaml

    Chart.yaml contains the metadata (information) about the Helm Chart.

        Think of it as the identity card or passport of the chart.

        It tells Helm:

        What is the chart name?
        What is the version?
        Who created it?
        What application does it deploy?
        Does it have dependencies?

    exapmle :
        apiVersion: v2
        name: springboot-app
        description: Helm chart for Spring Boot application
        type: application
        version: 0.1.0
        appVersion: "1.0.0"

values.yaml

    values.yaml stores the configurable values used by the Helm templates.


    Instead of hardcoding values in Kubernetes YAML, Helm stores them here.

    Examples:

    Number of replicas
    Docker image
    Image tag
    Service type
    Port
    Namespace
    Resource limits
    Environment variables
    Ingress host

    Example
        replicaCount: 2

        image:
        repository: nginx
        tag: "1.27"

        service:
        type: ClusterIP
        port: 80

charts/

    The charts/ directory stores dependent (child) Helm charts that your main chart depends on.

    Example 

    Imagine you're deploying your own application.

    Your application needs:
        MySQL Database
        Redis Cache

    Without Helm, you would install them separately:

    Application
    MySQL
    Redis

    Three separate installations.

    With Helm, you can package everything together.

    my-application-chart
    │
    ├── Application
    ├── MySQL Chart
    └── Redis Chart

    MySql and Redis charts are stored inside the chart/ directory



